		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~brendank310">brendank310</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~brendank310">( 915634 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64693920"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64693920">System Management Mode is generally regarded on x86 as ring(-3). Userspace is ring(3), kernel space is ring(0), and if a hypervisor is running that's generally ring(-1). System Management mode can also run a hypervisor (at least on Intel... I know, x86 is crazy). When you use a USB keyboard or something similar to interact with a BIOS, that's partially some drivers running in system management mode that are trapping back and forth between those contexts. SMM is about as game over as it gets.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64693920">

</div>
</div>

