	<div id="comment_top_64695048" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64695048" name="comment_link_64695048" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23417022&amp;cid=64695048" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64695048)" >They honestly can't just reflash good code?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64695048" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64695048); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~OneOfMany07">OneOfMany07</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~OneOfMany07">( 4921667 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64695048"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64695048"><p>I'm curious...  Yes, I know a hardware flashing device would be more secure, but could a flash of malware infected BIOS code really block another flash of safe BIOS code through the normal means?</p><p>Thinking more...  I guess if the flashing process was b0rkened, that might be how.  To always keep an area unchanged, or apply a break again.  Probably fragile to attempt, but it might be hard to recover from (again needing the hardware SPI programmer).</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64695048">

